english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Selection of Eight Masters of Tang and Song
  author: Seong Sam-mun
  language: eng
  text: "One day I obtained the Poetry Selection of Eight Masters of Tang and Song, compiled by the Unflagging Hall. I burned incense, straightened my robes, and read through it thrice with reverence. Then, bowing deeply, I spoke these words:\n\n\"The forms of poetry transform with the ages, yet what the learned must all master—what cannot change across ten thousand generations—consists of four types: the Elegant and Hymnic, the Elegies and Verses, Ancient Poetry, and Regulated Verse. The Elegant and Hymnic spring from the hands of the Sages, bearing the teachings meant to illuminate the world. The Elegies and Verses are the Commentary on the Songs of Chu compiled by Zhu Xi. Ancient Poetry comes from Liu Lü's selection. Scholars of the world know to revere and honor these. But when it comes to selections of Regulated Verse, though compiled by many hands, their selections amount merely to pairing the blue with white, to prizing the delicate over the robust. The great and noble find such work beneath them.\n\nObserving this selection, I see that works by masters beyond these eight are all set aside and not recorded. The excisions made are extraordinarily precise and rigorous—surpassing common understanding. Yet given the vast distance between ancient and modern times, and the multitude of poets, one might wonder: does choosing only eight masters and but a handful of their poems not seem too narrow? \n\nConsider: excellent jade does not come from Kunlun alone, yet when the world speaks of jade, Kunlun stands first—because Kunlun produces jade in abundance. Around Mount Kunlun, it is said even pebbles thrown at magpies turn to jade; thus jade is truly plentiful there. Yet from all that abundance, what is selected must possess that warmth and luminosity, that density and substance, that when struck rings clear and carries far—these possess something sublime beyond mere polish. So too does the gentleman select poetry: only works that spring from genuine feeling and bear upon virtue and teaching, works that truly move people toward good or away from evil—only these deserve selection.\n\nAh! Poetry reached its zenith in the Zhou dynasty, and what the Sages recorded for posterity—the entire canon of moral instruction—numbered merely three hundred and eleven poems. Yet after Qu Yuan, Song Yu, Su Wu, and Li Ling, poetic works multiplied manifold beyond the Zhou's abundance. Still, what Zhu Xi and Liu Xiang collated and preserved remained modest in number. Is poetry, then, so common? No—it is rare indeed.\n\nConfucius opened a pathway through the barrier of ages, illuminating the way for scholars. His single act of selection created this great service. Just as the Songs of Chu and selections of ancient poetry support the Elegant and Hymnic traditions and serve greatly the teachings of the Sages, so too does this present selection gather the finest works of worthy masters, filling gaps in poetic learning. Through it, present and future generations may taste poetry's lingering resonance, be moved and corrected by it—is this not the very aim of the wise and virtuous?\n\nHaving myself witnessed this excellence and beauty, I could not but set down these words.\""
  footnotes:
    - The 'Eight Masters of Tang and Song' refers to eight renowned poets whose works formed the core curriculum for serious study of poetry in East Asia.
    - The reference to '311 poems' alludes to the traditional count of poems in the Book of Poetry (Shijing), considered the canonical collection by Confucius.
    - Qu Yuan, Song Yu, Su Wu, and Li Ling represent the great post-classical poets whose works, while numerous, required careful selection to preserve their essential value.
    - The metaphor of jade from Kunlun illustrates the principle that true worth lies not in abundance but in exceptional quality and authenticity.
